item.title: Polish govt postpones presidential vote
item.description: Poland's ruling party leader and a partner in the governing coalition has announced an agreement to postpone Sunday's presidential election, saying a new date will be chosen later.

item.title: Govt urges Brits to ‘buy a newspaper’
item.description: British Housing Secretary Robert Jenrick has called on people to buy a newspaper in a bid to help publications make it through the COVID-19 shutdown.

item.title: Iceland almost recovered from virus: govt
item.description: Iceland has all but eliminated the coronavirus outbreak as 97 per cent of infected patients have recovered and only two new cases have been confirmed in the last week, the government says.

item.title: Israeli court paves way for govt formation
item.description: Israel's highest court has rejected petitions against another term for right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and a coalition agreement, paving the way for the formation of a government.

item.title: ACT students in staged return to school
item.description: Public school students in Canberra will return to their classrooms in stages over the next four weeks after schools shut due to coronavirus.

item.title: Kraftwerk co-founder Schneider dies at 73
item.description: Florian Schneider-Esleben - co-founder of German electronic-music pioneers Kraftwerk, one of the most influential music groups of the past 50 years - has died, a representative for the group says.

item.title: UK govt denies neglecting elderly in care
item.description: Prime Minister Boris Johnson says the situation in care homes has improved, hours after his health minister denied Britain had prioritised hospitals over many elderly people in its fight against the coronavirus outbreak.

item.title: China warns US over Trump tariff threat
item.description: China says tariffs should not be used as a weapon after US President Donald Trump threatened to impose more of them in retaliation for China's handling of the novel coronavirus.

item.title: Electronic votes approved in UK parliament
item.description: British MPs will be able to vote without attending the House of Commons chamber after Speaker Lindsay Hoyle authorised the "historic" move to electronic voting.

item.title: Baltic states to create ‘travel bubble’
item.description: Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia will open their borders to each others' citizens from May 15, creating a Baltic "travel bubble" within the European Union amid an easing of pandemic restrictions, their prime ministers say.
